    "markdown": "## Ultrasound SHORT SCAN at Cadabams Diagnostics | Quick & Safe\n\n## Ultrasound SHORT SCAN Overview\n### What the scan checks in under 15 minutes\n- \\*\\*Fetal femur length (FL)\\*\\* – key growth marker\n- \\*\\*Amniotic fluid index (AFI)\\*\\* – checks fluid levels\n- \\*\\*Placental position & maturity\\*\\* – ensures safe blood flow\n- \\*\\*Estimated fetal weight percentile\\*\\* – flags IUGR/SGA early\n### Why choose Cadabams Diagnostics for a fast ultrasound\n- \\*\\*Same-day booking\\*\\* via website or app\n- \\*\\*10-minute scan time\\*\\* with senior sonographers\n- \\*\\*Instant digital report\\*\\* straight to your phone\n- \\*\\*Thermal prints\\*\\* for keepsake photos\n## What is Ultrasound SHORT SCAN?\n### Definition and equipment used\nAn \\*\\*Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\\*\\* is a focused, low-frequency ultrasound exam that zeroes in on fetal growth indicators—mainly femur length—in just 10 minutes. We use \\*\\*state-of-the-art GE Voluson™\\*\\* machines with high-resolution 2D/3D probes for crystal-clear images.\n### Difference from full-length obstetric ultrasound\n| Feature | SHORT SCAN | Full Obstetric Scan |\n|---------|-----------|---------------------|\n| Duration | 10–15 min | 30–45 min |\n| Focus | FL, AFI, placenta | Complete anatomy survey |\n| When used | Follow-up or growth check | Routine anomaly scan |\n## Types of Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n### Transabdominal quick scan\n- Most common; probe glides over your belly\n- Requires comfortably full bladder for clearer images\n### Transvaginal short scan (if indicated)\n- Used only when placenta is very low or if BMI > 35\n- Takes 5 extra minutes; completely safe\n\n## When and Who Needs to Take an Ultrasound SHORT SCAN?\n- \\*\\*Pregnancies requiring femur length check\\*\\* after dating scan\n- \\*\\*High-risk IUGR or SGA cases\\*\\* flagged by your OB-GYN\n- \\*\\*Follow-up after prior short femur findings\\*\\* to track progression\n\n## Risks & Limitations of US Short Scan\n\n## Risks & Limitations of the Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n- \\*\\*Zero radiation risk\\*\\*—safe for fetus and mother\n- \\*\\*Possible inconclusive results\\*\\* when baby is in poor position; we’ll arrange a repeat scan same day at no extra charge\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During US Short Scan\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During the Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n1. \\*\\*Fetal femur length (FL)\\*\\* – growth yardstick\n2. \\*\\*Amniotic fluid index (AFI)\\*\\* – cushions baby\n3. \\*\\*Placental position & maturity\\*\\* – grades 0–III\n4. \\*\\*Estimated fetal weight percentile\\*\\* – identifies IUGR/SGA\n\n## Reasons for Taking an Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n- \\*\\*Screen for isolated short femur\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Monitor growth restriction trends\\*\\* week-to-week\n- \\*\\*Guide decision on genetic testing\\*\\* like NIPT or amnio\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n\n- \\*\\*Early detection\\*\\* of IUGR & SGA before complications arise\n- \\*\\*Quick appointment slots\\*\\*—book 7 AM–9 PM, even Sundays\n- \\*\\*Digital report\\*\\* shared instantly via \\*\\*Cadabams Diagnostics app\\*\\*\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n\n- \\*\\*Intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR)\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Placental insufficiency\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Skeletal dysplasia / short-limb syndromes\\*\\*\n\n## Preparing for US Short Scan\n\n## Pre-requisites Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n- \\*\\*Valid LMP date\\*\\* or dating scan reference\n- \\*\\*Doctor’s prescription recommended\\*\\* (walk-ins accepted)\n---\n## Best Time to Take the Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n- \\*\\*Second trimester:\\*\\* 20–24 weeks for baseline femur length\n- \\*\\*Third trimester:\\*\\* 28–36 weeks for growth-reassurance checks\n---\n## Eligibility\n- \\*\\*All pregnant women\\*\\* with clinical indication\n- \\*\\*BMI ≤ 35\\*\\* for optimal image quality (higher BMIs offered transvaginal route)\n---\n## Procedure for Taking an Ultrasound SHORT SCAN\n1. \\*\\*Check-in & consent (5 min)\\*\\*\n2. \\*\\*Scan duration (10 min)\\*\\*\n3. \\*\\*Post-scan report generation (5 min)\\*\\*\n---\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n- \\*\\*Notify sonographer\\*\\* of any bleeding or pain\n- \\*\\*Discontinue full bladder\\*\\* protocol if high-risk rupture suspected"
  },
